After sketching the primitive life and manners of mankind, he traces the progress of civilization, of religion, and of the various forms of government from their rudest beginnings3 in the spirit of a true Roman who had inherited the ancestral virtues, setting forth the family as the beginning and the grand means of human enlightenment, and associating with it music, as a powerful auxiliary in elevating the race from barbarism to civilized life.
